            {
                "s2_paper_id": "700f5ef527c7487a590cab24a1ca26e52e847696",
                "title": "Cicada emergence alters forest food webs",
                "year": 2025,
                "venue": "TheScienceBreaker",
                "citation_count": 0,
                "reference_count": 0,
                "abstract": "During a recent periodical cicada emergence, over 80 bird species altered their foraging behaviors to feed on the abundant insects. This diet shift reduced the rate of predation on forest caterpillars, doubling both their abundance and the amount of leaf tissue they consumed. Regional biomass pulses thus have the potential to disrupt the usual patterns of energy flow in forest ecosystems. \n\u00a0",
                "authors": [
                    {
                        "s2_author_id": "2260538323",
                        "name": "Martha Weiss"
                    },
                    {
                        "s2_author_id": "2342808122",
                        "name": "John Lill"
                    }
                ]
            },
            {
                "s2_paper_id": "173f657bf4eb95ea6ca318c35eeee3b1cda4d4b2",
                "title": "Periodical cicadas disrupt trophic dynamics through community-level shifts in avian foraging",
                "year": 2023,
                "venue": "Science",
                "citation_count": 15,
                "reference_count": 51,
                "abstract": "Once every 13 or 17 years within eastern North American deciduous forests, billions of periodical cicadas concurrently emerge from the soil and briefly satiate a diverse array of naive consumers, offering a rare opportunity to assess the cascading impacts of an ecosystem-wide resource pulse on a complex food web. We quantified the effects of the 2021 Brood X emergence and report that more than 80 bird species\u202fopportunistically switched their foraging to include cicadas, releasing herbivorous insects from predation and essentially doubling both caterpillar densities and accumulated herbivory levels on host oak trees. These short-lived but massive emergence events help us to understand how resource pulses can rewire interaction webs and disrupt energy flows in ecosystems, with potentially long-lasting effects. Description Editor\u2019s summary Periodical cicadas emerge en masse every 13 or 17 years, bringing not just a continuous drone of noise but also an influx of food for birds and other predators. Getman-Pickering et al. performed a set of experiments in the years before, after, and during the 2021 Brood X cicada emergence to determine how this addition of resources affected trophic dynamics in an eastern US forest (see the Perspective by Parker). They found that, compared with nonemergence years, cicada emergence led to lower caterpillar predation by birds, higher caterpillar densities, and lower herbivory rates on oak saplings. As birds opportunistically switched to cicada prey, their control over herbivory declined, showing the far-reaching short-term impacts of a resource pulse. \u2014Bianca Lopez A temporary abundance of cicadas reduces caterpillar predation by birds and increases herbivory on saplings in a US forest.",
